.TH CYBERHUB 1 "CyberHub User Manual"

.SH NAME
.B CyberHub -
.I A Complete Resource Hub For Cyber Security Community

.SH SYNOPSIS
.RI cyberhub
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ arguments ]

.SH INTRODUCTION
.B CyberHub
is an open source and free cybersecurity utility . It is designed as a comprehensive resource hub for the cybersecurity community.

CyberHub aims to be a one-stop solution for learners, practitioners, and security enthusiasts by providing easy access to tools, cheatsheets, and useful security-related utilities. The project is actively maintained and continuously updated with new and improved features.

Users are welcome to suggest new features or improvements for future releases.

.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.B --tools, -t
Directly access the Tools option.

.TP
.B --cheatsheet, -c
Directly access the Cheatsheet option.

.TP
.B --asnrecord, -asn
Retrieve ASN record information based on an IP address.

Example:

```
cyberhub --asnrecord -ip 8.8.8.8
```

.TP
.B --dnsrecord, -dns
Retrieve DNS record information for a domain, with an optional record type.

Example:

```
cyberhub --dnsrecord -domain example.com --record TXT
```

.TP
.B --default-password-gen, -pass
Generate a secure random password with customizable length and character sets.

Example:

```
cyberhub --default-password-gen -L 10
```

.TP
.B --http-status, -S
Fetch the HTTP status code of a domain.

Example:

```
cyberhub --http-status -D google.com
```

.TP
.B --screenshot, -s
Capture a screenshot of a website and save it to the /Screenshot directory.

Example:

```
cyberhub --screenshot -domain example.com
```

.TP
.B --remove-duplicate, -rd
Remove duplicate entries from a file.

Example:

```
cyberhub --remove-duplicate -f file.txt
```

.TP
.B --getip, -gip
Retrieve the IP address of a domain.

Example:

```
cyberhub --getip -D google.com
```

.SH ARGUMENTS

.TP
.B --domain, -D
Specify the domain name for relevant operations.

Example:

```
cyberhub --domain google.com
```

.TP
.B --ip, -ip
Specify the IP address for relevant operations.

Example:

```
cyberhub --ip 8.8.8.8
```

.TP
.B --record, -r
Specify the DNS record type.

Example:

```
cyberhub --record TXT
```

.TP
.B --upper, -u
Include uppercase letters in password generation.

.TP
.B --lower, -l
Include lowercase letters in password generation.

.TP
.B --digits, -d
Include digits in password generation.

.TP
.B --punctuation, -p
Include special characters in password generation.

.TP
.B --length, -L
Specify the length of the generated password.

Example:

```
cyberhub --length 12
```

.TP
.B --checkpassword, -C
Check the generated password against common password patterns.

.TP
.B --file, -f
Specify an input file for file-based operations.

Example:

```
cyberhub --file /path/to/file
```

.TP
.B --output, -o
Specify the output file path.

Example:

```
cyberhub --output /path/to/output
```

.SH FILES

.RI /usr/bin/cyberhub
: Path to the CyberHub executable file.

.SH ERROR HANDLING
.B CyberHub
handles invalid inputs gracefully by displaying clear and informative error messages. Users should refer to these messages for troubleshooting.